<DOC><DOCNO> AP890531-0200 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2310EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Antigua-Body     05-31 0237</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Antigua-Body,0242</SECOND><HEAD>Find Body Of Opposition Leader's Wife</HEAD><DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police said the partially naked,manacled body of the wife of a political opposition leader wasfound on a beach early Wednesday, three days after she was reportedmissing.   Arah Hector, wife of Caribbean Liberation Movement leader TimHector, disappeared from their farm Sunday. Swimmers found her bodyat Jabberwalk Beach north of St. John's, the capital.   Police said they had detained a man employed at the farm, whereMrs. Hector's glasses and parts of her clothing were found on theground Sunday. They said there was no indication of the motive.   The body was partially buried in the sand, with the hands tiedbehind the back and clothes wrapped around the neck, police said.They speculated that she was killed on the farm and buried at thebeach.   Mrs. Hector, in her early 40s, had three sons and led theMarxist party's Women's Action Group. Tim Hector was in London onWednesday and was traveling in North Africa last week.   The Hectors and their party, which is not represented in the15-seat legislature, recently began a campaign against drugtrafficking on the island. In recent editorials, the partynewspaper Outlet denounced government corruption and accused someministers of involvement in the drug trade.   The Foreign Ministry of the former British colony said thegovernment had asked Scotland Yard's assistance in theinvestigation.</TEXT></DOC>